load in data using brick from raster package. Notice the 4 separate layers. the plot function isnt the best for plotting thus below we use the image function.

img <- brick("13-Weedle.png")
img
## class       : RasterBrick 
## dimensions  : 800, 748, 598400, 4  (nrow, ncol, ncell, nlayers)
## resolution  : 1, 1  (x, y)
## extent      : 0, 748, 0, 800  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : NA 
## data source : /Users/ricardoherena/Documents/Machine Learning Pred  454/Image Reconition Notes/13-Weedle.png 
## names       : X13.Weedle.1, X13.Weedle.2, X13.Weedle.3, X13.Weedle.4 
## min values  :            0,            0,            0,            0 
## max values  :          255,          255,          255,          255
img <- setMinMax(img)

cellStats(img, range)
##      X13.Weedle.1 X13.Weedle.2 X13.Weedle.3 X13.Weedle.4
## [1,]            0            0            0            0
## [2,]          255          255          255          255
img@extent
## class       : Extent 
## xmin        : 0 
## xmax        : 748 
## ymin        : 0 
## ymax        : 800
plot(img, main = c("w1","w2","w3","w3"))

plotRGB(img)

Apparently The plot() function in R has a base setting for the number of pixels that it will plot (100,000 pixels).
